From the scatter plot below, a correlation can be observed between psoriasis severity (SAPASI) and DLQI. The Spearman correlation coefficient (0.6) indicates a moderate negative correlation, meaning that as disease severity increases, quality of life decreases. When further stratifying the relationship between SAPASI and DLQI by two categorical variablessex and clinical trial groupthe plots show no clear interaction effects. Specifically, neither sex nor trial group appears to meaningfully modify the relationship between age and DLQI.

Modelling

Based on the analyses above, age and SAPASI were found to have significant effects on DLQI. In contrast, clinical trial group and sex did not show clear interaction effects with these relationships. Therefore, interaction terms were not included in the final model.

Subsequent hypothesis testing further confirmed that the interaction effects (clinical arm SAPASI, gender SAPASI, clinical arm age, and gender age) were not significantly associated with DLQI (p < 0.01).

The distribution of SAPASI was not normally distributed and therefore did not meet the assumptions required for linear regression modeling. However, after applying a log transformation, the distribution of SAPASI became approximately normal.

Based on the analyses above, the following linear regression model was proposed to investigate the specific effects of age and SAPASI on DLQI (quality of life). Using the AIC criterion and hypothesis testing for model evaluation, the model below was identified as the best-fitting model.

\[ E[\text{DLQI} \mid \text{Age}, \text{SAPASI}, \text{Clinical Arms}] = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \log_2(\text{SAPASI}) + \beta_2 \text{Age} + \beta_3 \text{Clinical Arms} \]

The model fitting results are shown in Table 6. The estimated intercept () is 36, indicating that the average DLQI score among patients is 36. This suggests that, on average, psoriasis has only a small impact on patients quality of life, according to the DLQI classification (3538: small effect).

When patients in the ES treatment group were compared with those in the SC group under the same age and psoriasis severity, patients in the ES group had significantly higher quality of life than those in the SC group. Age was significantly positively associated with quality of life, whereas psoriasis severity was significantly negatively associated with quality of life (p < 0.05; see Table 6).

Holding age constant, a 10% increase in SAPASI was associated with a decrease in DLQI of log(1 + 10%) = 0.11. Holding psoriasis severity constant, a 10-year increase in age was associated with an expected increase of 0.46 in the DLQI score. 

mod_Qol3 <-lm(DLQI_Total~log2(SAPASI)+AgeYrs+ES.SC,data=F04_DLQI_without_outerlier)

Model Diagnostics and Goodness-of-Fit Assessment

The QQ plot below illustrates the normality of the residuals. The plot shows that the residuals closely follow a standard normal distribution, with no evident violation of the normality assumption. Most residual points lie on or close to the diagonal line, indicating that the residuals are approximately normally distributed and that the model provides a good fit.

Ordinal regression Models to Investigate the Effects of Individual Risk Factors on EQ-5D

Based on the visual analyses above, age was found to have a substantial impact on mobility and anxiety/depression dimensions of EQ-5D-5L. As EQ-5D-5L consists of five ordered levels to assess quality of life, it represents an ordinal outcome. Therefore, an ordinal regression model was considered appropriate for addressing this multi-level outcome.

In this study, the mobility dimensionwhere age showed the most pronounced effectwas selected for further analysis. For mobility, no patients were classified at the most severe level (Level 5); therefore, the results are presented for Levels 14 only.

Ordinal Regression Model Diagnostics

The goodness-of-fit of the ordinal regression model was evaluated using three hypothesis tests. All three tests produced p-values greater than the 0.05 significance level. Therefore, the null hypothesis H0:that the ordinal regression model provides an adequate fit to the datawas not rejected, indicating that the model fits the data well.

9.(PsA)

In the model below, Y=1 indicates the presence of PsA. Male patients were used as the reference group. Smoking history was categorized into three groups: never smoked, former smoker, and current smoker, which were coded as labels 1, 2, and 3, respectively.

A logistic regression model was used to predict the presence of PsA and to evaluate the effects of individual risk factors on disease status. The candidate risk factors initially considered included age, sex, smoking history, and duration of psoriasis. However, during the feature selection process, neither age nor duration of psoriasis showed a significant association with PsA status.

The p-values for sex and smoking history were 0.01 and 0.09, respectively (Table 13). With the confidence level set at 0.10, the alternative hypothesisthat sex and smoking history are associated with PsAwas accepted. These two factors were therefore identified as having a meaningful impact on PsA among the candidate variables.

\[ \log \left( \frac{P(Y=1)}{1-P(Y=1)} \right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Gender} + \beta_2 \text{Smoking history} \]

From the model fitting results below, the following conclusions can be drawn:

When two patients have the same smoking history, the odds of developing PsA for male patients are exp(0.81) = 2.2 times those for female patients. Under the same sex, current smokers have exp(0.38) = 1.5 times higher odds of developing PsA compared with former smokers, and former smokers have 1.5 times higher odds of PsA compared with patients who have never smoked.

The classification performance of the logistic regression model is illustrated by the ROC curve shown below, with an AUC of 0.64. This indicates that the model does not achieve strong discriminative performance in classifying whether patients have PsA. This result is not unexpected.

According to extensive research on PsA, its pathogenesis is highly complex. PsA is not only a dermatological condition but also a musculoskeletal disease. In the early stages, the primary manifestation is enthesitis, which is characterized by inflammation at the sites where ligaments or tendons attach to bone or muscle.

The predictors selected in this analysis did not include musculoskeletal-related variables; therefore, the classification performance of the model is only moderate. Although sex and patients lifestyle factors are indeed associated with the presence of PsA, these features alone are insufficient for accurate disease classification.

To develop an effective screening or classification model for PsA, more comprehensive clinical data related to musculoskeletal involvement are required. The TUDOR clinical project has already collected such data, which will enable more in-depth investigations in future studies.
